<subSubSection id="C3058B8FFFB10462FFF8FBCFFDA7FA3C" pageId="7" pageNumber="512" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BA0D804FFB10462FFF8FBCFFDA7FA3C" blockId="7.[113,1089,1033,1569]" pageId="7" pageNumber="512">
<emphasis id="B96B0416FFB10462FFF8FBCFFF66FBFC" bold="true" box="[113,230,1033,1057]" pageId="7" pageNumber="512">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body large (15.7–21.0 mm) and wide (5.1–7.0 mm). Labium reaching between metacoxae. Antennomere 1 long in both sexes, invariably longer than antennomere 2, as long as or sometimes even longer than pronotum. Sexual dimorphism well expressed, callar lobe strongly gibbose in males (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FFB10462FE05FBAFFE59FB5C" box="[396,473,1129,1153]" captionStart="Figs 13–16.13–15" captionStartId="12.[151,187,1173,1192]" captionTargetBox="[151,1119,226,1155]" captionTargetId="figure-10@12.[151,1126,219,1157]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 13–16.13–15 – Physopelta (Physopelta) robusta Stål, 1863: 13–14 – head and pronotum (13 – male, 14 – female), 15 – apex of male protibia. 16 – Physopelta (Physopelta) biguttata Stål, 1870. (Photos: L. Dembický)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5739967" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5739967/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="512">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
), weakly gibbose in females (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FFB10462FC9BFBAFFCE1FB5C" box="[786,865,1129,1153]" captionStart="Figs 13–16.13–15" captionStartId="12.[151,187,1173,1192]" captionTargetBox="[151,1119,226,1155]" captionTargetId="figure-10@12.[151,1126,219,1157]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 13–16.13–15 – Physopelta (Physopelta) robusta Stål, 1863: 13–14 – head and pronotum (13 – male, 14 – female), 15 – apex of male protibia. 16 – Physopelta (Physopelta) biguttata Stål, 1870. (Photos: L. Dembický)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5739967" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5739967/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="512">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
). Profemora in males strongly incrassate, ventral surface with longitudinal furrow in its entire length bordered with a number of spines on both sides (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FFB10462FE5EFB6FFD97FB1C" box="[471,535,1193,1217]" captionStart="Figs 1–5" captionStartId="8.[652,689,1051,1070]" captionTargetBox="[151,1127,219,1257]" captionTargetId="figure-10@8.[151,1126,219,1253]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 1–5. Physopelta (Physopelta) robusta Stål, 1863, male. 1 – fore coxae and trochanters (magnification 47×), 2 – detail of procoxa and basal portion of trochanter (stridulatoty process marked with white arrow) (70×), 3 – external scent efferent system (40×), 4 – detail of osti- ole and peritreme (140×), 5 – ventral surface of profemur (23×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Fig. 4), 0.5 mm (Figs 1–3), 1 mm (Fig. 5). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5739961" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5739961/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="512">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). In females profemora distinctly more slender, with fewer spines. Protibia ventrally with a strong anteapical tooth and a row of small denticles along its entire length in males (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FFB10462FE55FB2FFDA4FADC" box="[476,548,1257,1281]" captionStart="Figs 1–5" captionStartId="8.[652,689,1051,1070]" captionTargetBox="[151,1127,219,1257]" captionTargetId="figure-10@8.[151,1126,219,1253]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 1–5. Physopelta (Physopelta) robusta Stål, 1863, male. 1 – fore coxae and trochanters (magnification 47×), 2 – detail of procoxa and basal portion of trochanter (stridulatoty process marked with white arrow) (70×), 3 – external scent efferent system (40×), 4 – detail of osti- ole and peritreme (140×), 5 – ventral surface of profemur (23×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Fig. 4), 0.5 mm (Figs 1–3), 1 mm (Fig. 5). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5739961" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5739961/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="512">Figs 5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="1324C481FFB10462FDBAFB2FFDD0FADC" box="[563,592,1257,1281]" captionStart="Figs 13–16.13–15" captionStartId="12.[151,187,1173,1192]" captionTargetBox="[151,1119,226,1155]" captionTargetId="figure-10@12.[151,1126,219,1157]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 13–16.13–15 – Physopelta (Physopelta) robusta Stål, 1863: 13–14 – head and pronotum (13 – male, 14 – female), 15 – apex of male protibia. 16 – Physopelta (Physopelta) biguttata Stål, 1870. (Photos: L. Dembický)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5739967" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5739967/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="512">15</figureCitation>
), unarmed in females. Mesofemora of males ventrally with a row of small denticles, these missing in females. Allometry of males exists: the sexually dimorphic characters are much more expressed in some males than in others. Stridulatory organs in form of a large tooth (strigil) on protrochanter, matching a depression on ventral surface of procoxa (plectrum) (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FFB10462FDA7FAAFFD10FA5C" box="[558,656,1385,1409]" captionStart="Figs 1–5" captionStartId="8.[652,689,1051,1070]" captionTargetBox="[151,1127,219,1257]" captionTargetId="figure-10@8.[151,1126,219,1253]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 1–5. Physopelta (Physopelta) robusta Stål, 1863, male. 1 – fore coxae and trochanters (magnification 47×), 2 – detail of procoxa and basal portion of trochanter (stridulatoty process marked with white arrow) (70×), 3 – external scent efferent system (40×), 4 – detail of osti- ole and peritreme (140×), 5 – ventral surface of profemur (23×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Fig. 4), 0.5 mm (Figs 1–3), 1 mm (Fig. 5). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5739961" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5739961/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="512">Figs 1−2</figureCitation>
). Peritreme of metathoracic scent glands horizontal, more or less scimitar-shaped with rounded apex, from ostiole directed laterad to slightly posterolaterad (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FFB10462FEF8FA6FFE56FA1C" box="[369,470,1449,1473]" captionStart="Figs 1–5" captionStartId="8.[652,689,1051,1070]" captionTargetBox="[151,1127,219,1257]" captionTargetId="figure-10@8.[151,1126,219,1253]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 1–5. Physopelta (Physopelta) robusta Stål, 1863, male. 1 – fore coxae and trochanters (magnification 47×), 2 – detail of procoxa and basal portion of trochanter (stridulatoty process marked with white arrow) (70×), 3 – external scent efferent system (40×), 4 – detail of osti- ole and peritreme (140×), 5 – ventral surface of profemur (23×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Fig. 4), 0.5 mm (Figs 1–3), 1 mm (Fig. 5). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5739961" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5739961/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="512">Figs 3−4</figureCitation>
). Paramere with apex longer and narrower, outer margin basally angulately produced (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FFB10462FE22FA0FFD9BFA3C" box="[427,539,1481,1505]" captionStart="Figs 6–12" captionStartId="9.[780,817,1351,1370]" captionTargetBox="[112,1090,219,1557]" captionTargetId="figure-12@9.[112,1086,219,1553]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 6–12. Physopelta (Physopelta) robusta Stål, 1863. 6–7 – pygophore (6 – dorsal view, magnification 50×; 7 – lateral view, 47×). 8–12 – para- mere (different orientations, 150×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Figs 8–12), 0.5 mm (Figs 6–7). (SEM microgra- phs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5739965" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5739965/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="512">Figs 8−12</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3058B8FFFB10462FFF8FA2FFCB8F9FC" pageId="7" pageNumber="512" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA0D804FFB10462FFF8FA2FFCB8F9FC" blockId="7.[113,1089,1033,1569]" pageId="7" pageNumber="512">
<emphasis id="B96B0416FFB10462FFF8FA2FFEB2F9DC" bold="true" box="[113,306,1513,1537]" pageId="7" pageNumber="512">Included species.</emphasis>
There are three species placed in 
<taxonomicName id="4C1FA387FFB10462FD1FFA2CFC8DF9DC" authorityName="Amyot &amp; Serville" authorityYear="1843" box="[662,781,1514,1537]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="512" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">
<emphasis id="B96B0416FFB10462FD1FFA2CFC8DF9DC" box="[662,781,1514,1537]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="512">Physopelta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A258B96DFFB10462FC9AFA2FFCCCF9DD" box="[787,844,1513,1536]" pageId="7" pageNumber="512" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, all of them distributed in the 
<collectingRegion id="49DB16E6FFB10462FF3DF9CFFEE3F9FC" box="[180,355,1545,1569]" country="Republic of the Congo" name="Orientale" pageId="7" pageNumber="512">Oriental Region</collectingRegion>
. I am not aware of any undescribed species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
